If you never want to modify a value inside `foo` after creation (&quot;immutable&quot;) and use Java 14 or newer, you can simply create a `record` (and please name it with an uppercase letter in the beginning for classes and records and enums).

If you need the `of` method, you can also add that to a record as you would do it for a class.

```lang-java
public record Foo (String flag, String id, String third) {
  public Foo of(String flag, String id, String third) {
    return new Foo(flag, id, third);
  } 
}
```

&quot;Downside&quot;: it doesn&#39;t have a private constructor, so the `of` method is quite useless probably - but it&#39;s the same as for the implementation you showed.

A `record` will automatically have the fields, a constructor with parameters to initialize the fields, proper implementation of `equals` and `hashcode` that takes all of the fields into account and a `toString` method that prints the values of the fields.

Oh, not to forget also a getter method for each field.

