I broke up your monolithic code into methods.

A method is a block of code that only runs when it is called.  You can pass data, known as parameters, into a method.  Methods are used to perform certain actions, and they are also known as functions.  Why use methods? To reuse code: define the code once, and use it many times.

Oracle has a helpful tutorial, [Creating a GUI With Swing](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/index.html).  Skip the Learning Swing with the NetBeans IDE section.  

Swing applications must start with a call to the `SwingUtilities` `invokeLater` method.  This method ensures that the Swing components are created and executed on the [Event Dispatch Thread][1].

Here&#39;s the complete runnable code.

    import java.awt.BorderLayout;
    import java.awt.Color;
    import java.awt.Dimension;
    import java.awt.Font;
